===Etymology===
Middle English ''[[plese]]'' < Middle {{F.}} ''[[plaisir]]'' < Latin ''[[placere|placēre]]'' ('to please', 'to seem good').

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/pliːz/}}
*{{audio|en-us-please.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-iːz|-iːz]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb|pleas|ing}}

# {{transitive}} To make [[happy]] or [[satisfy]]; to give [[pleasure]].
#: ''Her presentation '''pleased''' the executives.''
# {{intransitive}} To [[desire]]; to [[will]].
#: ''Just do as you '''please'''.''

====Synonyms====
*{{italbrac|to make happy}}: [[satisfy]]
*{{italbrac|to desire}}: [[desire]], [[will]]

====Antonyms====
*{{italbrac|to make happy}}: [[disgust]], [[displease]]

